The CoFe-LDH/MoS2@NDCDs catalyst was characterized using the Brunauer‒Emmett‒Teller (BET) isotherm curve, which enabled the calculation of a surface area of 12.4 m2/g. In comparison, the surface areas of CoFe-LDH@MoS2 and CoFe-LDH were 11.3 and 8.13 m2/g, respectively, as illustrated in Fig. 4
                     .The analysis of cumulative pore volumes in relation to pore diameter of these materials indicates notably narrower pore size distributions for CoFe-LDH/MoS2@NDCDs (ranging from 0 to 125 nm) in comparison to CoFe-LDH (ranging from 0 to 250 nm) and CoFe-LDH@MoS2 (ranging from 0 to 160 nm) (see Fig. S9). The pore distribution of CoFe-LDH appeared considerably broader. These findings suggest that the incorporation of carbon dots onto the LDH surfaces resulted in a more constrained pore distribution for the synthesized LDHs compared to those without support. Among the samples, CoFe-LDH/MoS2@NDCDs exhibited the highest pore volume with lower pore size (as shown in Table 1
                     ), which is advantageous for enhancing catalytic activity, as further discussed below. In essence, the attachment of LDH onto carbon substrates augmented both surface area and pore volume, underscoring the pivotal role of carbon support in LDH pore formation. This phenomenon contributed to amplified surface areas, narrower pore distribution, and increased pore volume [41]. Hence, the larger surface area, larger pore volume and smaller average pore size observed in CoFe-LDH/MoS2@NDCDs compared to the other LDH materials could potentially enhance its catalytic performance [42].
